 content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.305095074&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.305095074/asset/images/095074fig15b.jpeg" height="1653" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.305095074&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.305095074/asset/images/095074fig16.jpeg" height="1182" width="1620" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span> HCM in a 46-year-old man with recurrent ventricular tachycardia. Serial short-axis DE MR images show the patchy enhancement with multiple foci (arrowheads) in the asymmetric hypertrophic apical to basal wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.305095074&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.305095074/asset/images/095074fig17.jpeg" height="1199" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span> Midventricular to apical HCM in a 67-year-old man with chest discomfort. Short-axis first-pass perfusion MR images obtained with the patient at rest (upper row) and with adenosine-induced stress (lower row) demonstrate a reversible perfusion defect (subendocardial ring of low-signal-intensity enhancement on only the stress perfusion images) at the apical to the midventricular LV wall (arrowheads), a finding that is suggestive of inducible ischemia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.305095074&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Maron BJ, McKenna WJ, Danielson GK, et al. American College of Cardiology/European Society of Cardiology clinical expert consensus document on hypertrophic cardiomyopathy: a report of the American College of Cardiology Foundation Task Force on Clinical Expert Consensus Documents and the European Society of Cardiology Committee for Practice Guidelines. <em>J Am Coll Cardiol</em> 2003;42(9):1687–1713.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0735-1097(03)00941-0">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/14607462/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=American+College+of+Cardiology%2FEuropean+Society+of+Cardiology+clinical+expert+consensus+document+on+hypertrophic+cardiomyopathy%3A+a+report+of+the+American+College+of+Cardiology+Foundation+Task+Force+on+Clinical+Expert+Consensus+Documents+and+the+European+Society+of+Cardiology+Committee+for+Practice+Guidelines&amp;author=BJ+Maron&amp;author=WJ+McKenna&amp;author=GK+Danielson&amp;publication_year=2003&amp;journal=J+Am+Coll+Cardiol&amp;pages=1687-1713&amp;doi=10.1016%2FS0735-1097%2803%2900941-0&amp;pmid=14607462">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citatio